TY  - JOUR
AB  - Despite the potential benefits of agricultural insurance in helping farmers adapt to climate risks, its uptake among smallholder farmers remains limited. This study analyses the drivers of awareness and adoption of agricultural insurance in Nigeria to better understand the adoption process. 1,080 farming households were surveyed across six agro-ecological zones in Nigeria, covering areas with different socio-economic characteristics of farmers and levels of climate risk. Data were collected through face-to-face interviews between October 2020 and February 2021. The results show that more than half of the farmers were unaware of agricultural insurance. Logit regression results show that education, herd size, access to a bank, weather information, and flood experience positively influence awareness and adoption of agricultural insurance. In addition to low awareness, the main barriers to adoption are lack of knowledge about the effectiveness of insurance, difficulty in affording insurance, and farmers' low level of trust in insurance providers. Late payment of claims and inadequate compensation were the main challenges faced by adopters of agricultural insurance. Raising awareness and helping farmers to assess the effectiveness of agricultural insurance, as well as developing a supportive institutional environment, would help to build a well-functioning insurance market.
