AB  - Eleven papers examine selected food crops and agri-food policy challenges and their implications in various African countries, considering how current policies could be improved to achieve the continental vision of sustainable development in light of the African Union's Agenda 2063. Papers discuss the technical efficiency of poultry farmers in Cross River State, Nigeria; the economics of sesame marketing in Benue State, Nigeria; factors that influence smallholder maize farmers' technical efficiency and farm management practices in western Cameroon; the structure, conduct, and performance of tomato retailers in Ogun State, Nigeria; determinants of credit accessibility and performance of smallholder rice farmers in Cameroon; the impact of the yield of selected cereal crops on food security and agricultural growth in Nigeria; the effect of climate change and climate variability on Arabica coffee production in Uganda; the effect of private investment on groundnut output in Nigeria from 1980 to 2016; the need for a comprehensive policy option that will turn the fortunes of farmers toward improved agricultural productivity and increased access to food; government agricultural expenditure and agricultural growth in Nigeria from 1999 through 2020; and the public external debt, private investment, and agricultural output nexus. Odularu teaches in the Department of Economics and Business at the Virginia Military Institute. No index.
