AB  - Seventeen papers analyze the micro-behavioral economics of climate change, investigating how changes in climate policy and in nature will force economic agents to alter their choices. Papers discuss the economics of global tropical cyclones; efficient adaptation to global sea level rises; the impacts of climate change in the Ganges-Brahmaputra-Meghna River Delta; the challenges faced by the archipelagoes and small island nations in the South Pacific and Caribbean Sea; the impact of climate change on Thailand's rice agriculture; adaptation options for climate-change-impacted water resources in the Indu-Gangetic basin; the history of the Pampas biome in Latin America; sustainable intensification of agricultural productions in the Pampas grasslands; income source diversification strategies by Kenyan and East African farmers; whether climate change in the twenty-first century will impact hydroelectricity generation in the global community; a case study of hydropower projects in Nepal; the biogas production system being developed in Latin American countries; Europe's agricultural greenhouse gas emissions mitigation efforts via emission reduction credits; how the UN members who signed the Paris Agreement in 2015 have followed up with their commitment; the micro-behavioral aspects of the Green Climate Fund (GCF); GCF-funded water projects in Sri Lanka and India; and GCF grant allocations to Kenya and Ethiopia. Seo is with the Muaebak Institute of Global Warming Studies. Index.
