AB  - Seventeen papers examine social enterprises for addressing the global challenges of rising inequality, sustainable development, and climate change, focusing on cooperatives in the Asia-Pacific region. Papers discuss the theories and concept of social innovation; literature on social innovations in cooperatives; health insurance as social innovation for Indian farmers in cooperatives; community-based tourism in Malaysia as social innovation to improve the status of rural communities through cooperative principles; how biodiesel production by Japanese cooperatives addressed peoples' needs following natural disasters; the role of cooperatives in climate smart agriculture; advocating for the work of cooperatives using social media; the provision of long-term youth leadership training in cooperatives in the Philippines; the social innovations of a cooperative bank for female informal workers in India; the grading of financial cooperatives as social innovation; organic food innovations in drought-prone areas in rain-fed India; social innovative practices adopted by Indian industrial and agricultural marketing cooperatives; products and processes that advanced the consumer cooperative movement in Japan; how worker cooperatives addressed the concerns of Filipino workers in a contractual employment arrangement; the promotion of female leadership in Indian dairy cooperatives; economically targeted investing and crowdfunding innovations by worker cooperatives; and relief and remedial measures initiated by cooperatives to protect the interests of members and a local community hit by the COVID-19 pandemic. Rajasekhar is HAG Professor in Economics with the Centre for Decentralisation and Development at the Institute for Social and Economic Change. Manjula is Assistant Professor with the Centre for Decentralisation and Development at the Institute for Social and Economic Change. The late Paranjothi was Director of the Agricultural Cooperative Staff Training Institute. No index.
