AB  - Ten papers explore climate change's impacts on food production systems, focusing on Bangladesh, India, and Nepal. Papers discuss the duality of the relationship between climate change and agriculture; research and capacity gaps in policies, institutions, and markets in the eastern Indo-Gangetic Plain, including the states of Bihar and West Bengal in India, Nepal, and Bangladesh; the dynamic nature of small farm holdings in India; the gap between scientific knowledge about smart agriculture technologies and the farmers' preferences in Madhya Pradesh; farmers' preferences and willingness to pay for various climate-smart interventions in the Indo-Gangetic Plain; a modeling approach to upscale climate smart agriculture (CSA) technologies to simulate the impacts and costs of climate change at the national level; whether the various drought-proofing and drought-relief programs are effective in mitigating the impact of droughts on crop production and household consumption in rural Bihar, India; the efficacy of institutional and technological measures in reducing farmers' vulnerability and increasing their adaptation to climatic extremes; features of weather index-based crop insurance, including index-based flood insurance, and its performance in India and other developing countries; and the impact of irrigation and fertilizer policies in combating climate change issues in Indian agriculture. Pal is Program Manager at the International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) South Asia Regional Office. Kishore is Research Fellow at the IFPRI South Asia Regional Office. Joshi is Director of the IFPRI South Asia Regional Office. Tyagi is with the International Development Centre Foundation, Ghaziabad. No index.
