AB  - Twelve papers explore socioeconomic impact assessments for genetically modified organisms, including genetically modified crops, providing case studies involving Bt cotton and other selected crops with improved traits from six major institutions in India. Papers discuss the origins of the Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety; the importance of shared understanding on core elements of socioeconomic assessment; the methodology and analytical methods applied in the six studies to estimate costs and benefits of cultivating potential living modified (genetically modified) organisms (LMOs); notions of risk, benefits, and expectations from technology in the debate on LMOs and their socioeconomic assessment; the socioeconomic assessment of LMOs in Punjab and Haryana; insect resistance and herbicide tolerance traits in maize and brinjal in Tamil Nadu; an ex ante scenario of farmers adopting drought- and saline-resistant genetically modified varieties in ground nuts and castor; the socioeconomic implications of LMOs, such as Bt cotton, in comparison to traditional or pigeon pea in North Karnataka; methods and application for assessment of adoption and impact of LMOs in Telangana; a socioeconomic assessment in Karnataka with special focus on the drought tolerance trait of aerobic rice and the insect resistance trait of Bt cotton; frameworks and guidelines for socioeconomic assessment; and new trends in technology and the relevance of socioeconomic assessment. Chaturvedi is Director General at the Research and Information System for Developing Countries. Srinivas is Consultant to the Research and Information System for Developing Countries. Index.
