AB  - This dissertation presents three essays on labor and development economics. Each chapter examines a factor that affects household labor demand and supply for each household member and its implications in low- and middle-income countries. Research in this dissertation takes advantage of detailed household surveys and satellite collected environmental data to study the effects of climate on social outcomes. This data is then used to conduct empirical analysis of intra-household allocation of time and resources. In Chapter 1, I apply an economic lens to examine how water scarcity affects household water consumption and the (time) cost to obtain water. Using a longitudinal data set together with the exogeneity of weather shocks as identification strategies, I estimated the impact of drought on household water consumption and the cost of obtaining water, including time spent fetching water in Uganda. In Chapter 2, I assess the labor supply and welfare impacts of a Bolivian policy change in 2014 that lowered the minimum working age. Finally, in Chapter 3, I examine the household characteristics particularly associated with children working in hazardous environments in Nepal. In my first chapter, I estimate the intra-household time allocation of costs associated with climate shocks. Although the World Health Organization suggests that twenty liters of water per person per day is essential to satisfy basic daily activity needs, obtaining water is not costless. Moreover, the burden of obtaining water is expected to rise in response to climate change induced water shortages incurred by different household members. This research provides some of the first empirical evidence on how rainfall scarcity affects water consumption and the cost of obtaining water using a nationally representative panel and satellite precipitation data from Uganda. I document a decrease in the use of surface water and an increase in distance and waiting time at the water source for drought-hit households. Reflecting water demand's inelastic nature, households do not reduce water consumption due to water supply shocks. Instead, households hit by droughts are more likely to pay user fees for water and increase time spent fetching water, compared to years without a drought. Results suggest that women and girls are the ones who spend more time fetching water in order to meet the additional burden. This study highlights the undocumented cost of weather shocks on vulnerable households and inequitable costs for members within a household. In my second chapter, I conduct an impact evaluation of the government policy to legalize child labor. Although many global policies seek to limit child labor, some argue that this additional labor can help households living in poverty. Despite the controversy, no previous empirical study documents how legalizing child labor impacts the labor supply of children. In August 2014, Bolivia lowered its minimum working age from 14 to 10. Using difference-indifference, this paper shows that the policy increased participation in family work for boys aged 12-13 but had no effect on girls' labor. The effect is explained by an increase in agricultural labor. Boys aged 12-13 from farm households are ten percentage points more likely to work due to this policy change. This paper finds no policy effect on schooling outcomes, at least in the short-term. Consistent with an increase in agricultural labor, families with children exposed to the policy increased household monthly food consumption from their farms. Finally, in the third chapter, I investigate the nature of hazardous forms of child labor and household characteristics associated to this type of child labor. Using Nepal's first nationwide household survey that incorporates a module (Multiple Indicator Cluster Survey Module 5, Nepal 2014) on children's working conditions, this paper investigates the factors that drive children into hazardous forms of labor. While the importance of eliminating the hazardous and worst forms of child labor has been addressed for many years, quantitative evidence on what household characteristics lead children to work in hazardous environments is scarce. The new finding from this paper is that, even among children who are engaged in child labor, children from poorer households are more likely to engage in hazardous forms of child labor. Similarly, household characteristics such as father's absence due to death, and children living without parental care result in higher risk of children engaging in hazardous labor. The evidence from the empirical analysis about associated factors for hazardous child labor helps policymakers identify families at high risk.
