AB  - Analyzes the region-specific impacts of climate change on the productivity and production of rice in India, outlining a series of adaptation strategies to address such impacts. Provides an overview of climate change, the challenges it poses for ensuring water and food security, and the need for alternative adaptation strategies to reduce variability. Discusses rice location, production, and productivity trends in India. Describes the methodology and approach used for extracting future climate change projections for India's major rice-growing states. Explains the approach used to quantify climate change impacts on rice production. Investigates the perceptions of farmers on climate change and its effect on rice productivity and production in India's northern, eastern, western, central, and southern regions. Considers the financial viability of climate-smart adaptation practices at the farm level. Discusses recommendations for stabilizing rice productivity and production in the future. Palanisami is Principal Researcher with the International Water Management Institute. Kakumanu is Associate Professor with the Centre for Natural Resource Management at the National Institute of Rural Development and Panchayati Raj. Nagothu is Research Professor and Director of the Centre for International Development with the Norwegian Institute of Bioeconomy Research. Ranganathan is Adjunct Professor in the Department of Computing at the Coimbatore Institute of Technology. No index.
