AB  - Twenty-four papers bring together the research, analyses, and opinions of agricultural and resource economists and policy experts to develop the conceptual, empirical, and policy basis for a better understanding of climate-smart agriculture (CSA). Papers discuss a short history of the evolution of the CSA approach and its links to climate change and sustainable agriculture debates; the economics of CSA; innovation in response to climate change; the use of satellite information on wetness and temperature for crop yield prediction and river resource planning; early warning techniques for local climate resilience; farmers' perceptions of and adaptations to climate change in Southeast Asia; US maize yield growth and countervailing climate-change impacts; an application of decision-support tools for assessing CSA; whether insurance can help manage climate risk and food insecurity; whether cash-transfer programs can promote household resilience; input subsidy programs and CSA; robust decision making for a climate-resilient development of the agricultural sector in Nigeria; the Agricultural Model Inter-comparison and Improvement Project regional integrated assessment methods for evaluating vulnerability, resilience, and adaptive capacity for CSA systems; climate-smart food supply chains in developing countries; the adoption of CSA and the role of information and insurance under climate change; a qualitative evaluation of CSA options in mixed crop-livestock systems in developing countries; identifying strategies to enhance the resilience of smallholder farming systems; climate risk management through sustainable land and water management in sub-Saharan Africa; improving the resilience of Central Asian agriculture to weather variability and climate change; the role of adaptation in the Nile Basin of Ethiopia; diversification as part of a CSA strategy; an economic analysis of improved smallholder paddy and maize production in Northern Vietnam and implications for climate-smart agriculture; devising effective strategies and policies for CSA; and the policy implications of CSA--building resilience to climate change. Lipper is at ISPC-CGIAR. McCarthy is at Lead Analytics Inc. Zilberman is with the Department of Agriculture and Resource Economics at the University of California, Berkeley. Asfaw is with the Food and Agriculture Organization at the United Nations. Branca is in the Department of Economics at the University of Tuscia. Index.
