AB  - Eleven papers examine the state and prospects of the agricultural sector in sub-Saharan Africa, presenting policy options for enhancing its resilience and sustainability in terms of productivity, climate change resilience, and industrialization. Papers discuss improved maize seeds and agricultural productivity of family farms in Cameroon; drivers of agricultural technology adoption by smallholder farmers in Zimbabwe; the influence of input utilization on labor productivity among Nigerian men and women; women's involvement in on-farm trials of agricultural technologies in Nigeria; the impact of bioenergy crop adoption on total crop incomes of farmers in northern Ghana; solutions to combat land degradation and desertification; the vulnerability of villages to climate shocks and land tenure's effect on vulnerability in Benin; the effect of drought index insurance on the demand for supplemental irrigation in Northern Ghana; the effect of the agriculture sector's development on the manufacturing sector in Africa; the role that special economic zones can play in transforming Africa's agriculture and developing agribusiness markets; and global value chains and upgrading in the Economic Community of West African States countries. Shimeles is Acting Director of the Macroeconomic Policy, Forecasting, and Research Department at the African Development Bank. Verdier-Chouchane is Chief Research Economist at the African Development Bank. Boly is Principal Research Economist at the African Development Bank. Index.
