AB  - In this dissertation, I study three topics in applied microeconomics and development economics. The first chapter, co-authored with Madhulika Khanna, examines how the marriage market responds to the flooding of the river Kosi in 2008 in Bihar, one of the poorest regions in the world and with high rates of child marriage. To identify the effects of the Kosi floods, we compare outcomes for marriages that formed before the Kosi floods with outcomes for marriages that formed after the Kosi floods between affected and unaffected districts in Bihar in a difference-in-differences framework. We find that the Kosi floods reduced men's and women's age at marriage, decreased the secondary school completion rate of married men and women, and married women's command over economic resources. We interpret these results within a framework of marriage market: in the absence of complete credit markets, marriage market payments (dowry) help smooth consumption when faced with adverse income shocks due to floods. Policies such as disaster insurance or low-cost credit may play a critical role in weakening this link between marriage markets and natural disasters. The second paper, co-authored with Caitlin Brown and Garance Genicot, studies how the 'effective' term limits imposed by next-period reservations for women worsen the elite capture in Indian villages. First, in a theoretical model, we illustrate the allocation of public resources as a trade-off between the incumbent's incentive to increase their future electoral prospects and their incentive to cater to elites. We then estimate the differences in public resource allocations between term- and non-term-limited village presidents using detailed data from India. We find that term-limited presidents provide relatively fewer public goods to heavily populated streets (with many potential votes) and instead allocate more public goods to the streets of the landed elite. We also find that term-limited presidents provide more private benefits to landed households. Our findings have important implications for interpreting the effects of political reservations and the understanding of elite capture in rural India. The third chapter, co-authored with Erwin Knippenberg, studies the effect of the 2018 droughts on consumption and poverty in Afghanistan. We combine geo-located data from the 2019-20 household income and expenditure survey with historical weather data on precipitation, vegetation, and temperature indicators. We construct standardized measures of weather shocks (z-score) and exploit the spatial variation in the intensity of shock across districts. First, we show that temperature and vegetation shocks are better measures of drought than precipitation anomalies in arid to semi-arid conditions like in Afghanistan. Second, we find that droughts, measured by temperature or vegetation shocks, decreased monthly per capita consumption expenditures and increased poverty rates. The effects of temperature shocks were stronger in Taliban-controlled districts. Additionally, households reduced per capita non-food spending to protect themselves from food insecurity, and those owning agricultural land or livestock were more resilient to the 2018 droughts. Based on the historical distribution of weather shocks, simulations estimate 61 percent of people have a one in four probability of falling into poverty due to droughts over the decade, compared to 47 percent poor in 2018. Since our sample excludes households displaced into settlements, these results are underestimates.
