AB  - Twenty-one papers, originally presented at the September 2015 World Symposium on Climate Change Adaptation held in Manchester, demonstrate how to pursue and implement adaptation initiatives in cities, communities, and regions. Papers cover issues pertaining to adaptation on both urban and rural levels and focus on the integration of adaptation strategies and educational approaches. Papers discuss changes in land-cover categories within the Oti-Keran-Mandouri complex in Togo (West Africa) between 1987 and 2013; the exposure of rural communities to climate variability and change--case studies from Argentina, Colombia, and Canada; small-scale rain and floodwater harvesting for horticulture in central-northern Namibia for livelihood improvement and as an adaptation strategy to climate change; whether adaptation to climate change can be at all mainstreamed in complex multilevel governance systems--a case study of forest-relevant policies at the EU and Swedish levels; a novel impact-assessment methodology for evaluating distributional impacts in Scottish climate-change adaptation policy; climate variability and food security in Tanzania--evidence from Western Bagamoyos; the urban heat island effect in Dutch city centers--identifying relevant indicators and first explorations; planning and climate change--a case study on the spatial plan of the Danube Corridor through Serbia; programs from the Republic of Belarus on climate-change adaptation--goals and results; a global indicator of climate-change adaptation in Catalonia; facilitating climate-change adaptation on smallholder farms through farmers' collective-led on-farm adaptive research--the Strengthening Adaptive Farming in Bangladesh, India, and Nepal project; assessing student perceptions and comprehension of climate change in Portuguese higher-education institutions; a decade of capacity building through roving seminars on agro-meteorology/-climatology in Africa, Asia, and Latin America--from agrometeorological services via climate change to agroforestry and other climate-smart agricultural practices; West African farmers' climate-change adaptation--moving from technological change toward transforming institutions; livelihood options as adaptation to climate variability among households in rural southwest Nigeria--emerging concerns and reactions; climate-change projections for a medium-sized urban area (Baia Mare Town, Romania)--local awareness and adaptation constraints; trends and issues of climate-change education in Japan; changes in attitude toward climate change and transformative learning theory; societal transformation and buzzy perspectives toward successful climate change adaptation--an appeal to caution; an analysis of climate change adaptation measures used by rural dwellers in the southeast and south-south zones of Nigeria; and science field shops--an innovative agricultural extension approach for adaptation to climate change, applied with farmers in Indonesia. Leal Filho is with the Research and Transfer Center in the Faculty of Life Sciences at the Hamburg University of Applied Sciences. Adamson and Dunk are in the School of Science and the Environment at Manchester Metropolitan University. Azeiteiro and Alves are with the Centre for Functional Ecology at Coimbra University and the University of Aberta. Illingworth is in the School of Research, Enterprise at Manchester Metropolitan University. No index.
