AB  - Sixteen papers examine the challenges and opportunities for building an economy and society that is more resilient to climate change. Papers discuss the environmental impact of climate-change adaptation on land use and water quality; the adaptive capacity contributing to improved agricultural productivity at the household level--empirical findings highlighting the importance of crop insurance; adapting to climate change and improving urban resilience--the role of nature and biodiversity protection in cities; coproducing resilience through understanding vulnerability; climate resilience and sustainable development--challenges and options for small-island developing states; whether agriculture can be climate smart; global warming and changes in marine ecosystems--economic consequences and adjustment issues; climate change, marine ecosystems, and global fisheries; extreme drought and California's water economy--challenges and opportunities for building resilience; building urban climate resilience in Vietnam and Bangladesh; renewable-energy economics; carbon-pricing policy design and revenue management--economic models and policy practice; reducing emissions from deforestation and forest degradation plus (REDD+)--a global multilevel forest governance for building a climate-resilient society; democratizing climate finance at local levels; whether climate policies hurt the economy--lessons from the EU experience; and claiming the sky--the atmosphere as a community asset. Ninan is Chairperson with the Centre for Economics, Environment and Society in Bangalore, and Co-Chair of the Panel on Methodological Assessment of Scenarios and Models of Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services with the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services at the United Nations. Inoue is Professor of Environmental Sociology in the Faculty of Human Sciences at Waseda University. Index.
