AB  - Seventeen papers examine topics in global agriculture and food security. Papers discuss assessing the impact of agricultural research and development investments on long-term projections of food security; the nexus of dietary guidelines and food security; food security through biotechnology--the case of genetically modified sugar beets in the United States; what would happen if genetically modified organism plant materials were banned; climate change and food security--threats and adaptation; climate change and food security--Florida's agriculture in the coming decades; vegetable production, diseases, and climate change; US agricultural policy--the impacts on domestic and international food security; sugarcane yields and production--Florida and Louisiana; aquaculture--its role in the future of food; food security and the Food Safety Modernization Act; agricultural biotechnology and food security--whether the Canada-EU Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement, Trans-Pacific Partnership, and Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership can become venues to facilitate trade in genetically modified products; assessing food security in Ethiopia; the coffee-food security interface for subsistence households in Jimma Zone, Ethiopia; assessing food security in rural Bangladesh--the role of a nonfarm economy; food costs during the food crisis--the case of Tanzania; and food loss and waste as an economic and policy problem. Andrew Schmitz is at the University of Florida. Kennedy is at Louisiana State University. Troy G. Schmitz is at Arizona State University. Index.
