AB  - Twenty-two papers present recent developments in resource economics, providing critical assessment of new discoveries, and identify new promising directions for research. Papers focus on a conversation with Emery Neal Castle; the economics of US state and local regulation of farm practices; certification mechanisms for credence attributes of foods; intellectual property rights and the ascent of proprietary innovation in agriculture; the economics of farm animal welfare; whether water-quality trading can fix the agricultural nonpoint source problem; managing climate change under uncertainty; integrated assessment models of the food, energy, and water nexus; air and water--integrated assessment models for multiple media; adopting an integrated framework for sustainability; adaptation to climate change; green innovation and market power; green industrial policy in emerging markets; measuring the bioeconomy; spillovers from conservation programs; asking willingness-to-accept questions in stated-preference surveys; household response to time-varying electricity prices; life-cycle assessment for economists; perceived self-efficacy, poverty, and economic development; secondary towns and poverty reduction; index insurance for developing-country agriculture; and transitioning toward nutrition-sensitive food systems in developing countries. Rausser and Zilberman are at the University of California, Berkeley. No index.
