AB  - Technical and allocative efficiency measures are derived for a sample of aman rice producers in Bangladesh using the parametric stochastic frontier and nonparametric data envelopment analysis (DEA). Efficiency measures obtained from the two frontier approaches are compared. Firm-specific factors affecting productive efficiencies are also analysed. Finally, rice producers' potential for reducing cost through improved efficiency is also examined. The results show that human labour, draft power, and urea make important contributions to the output of both local (LV) and modern varieties (MV). For the local variety (LV), mean technical and allocative efficiency using a parametric stochastic approach was 83.5% and 89.96% respectively, while those were 82.53% and 86.35% respectively for DEA approach. The modern variety (MV) efficiency results are similar, but a few points higher. On average, the estimated technical and allocative efficiencies are significantly higher in the DEA technique than in parametric method, while allocative efficiencies are generally higher in the parametric approach than in the DEA method. These mixed results among the two frontier approaches demonstrate the need for more empirical work to further examine the performance of the two approaches using the same data sets. However, the ranking of farms by efficiency suggests that the farm identified as being the most technically efficient for both varieties remains the most allocative efficient as well. The results also followed the expected pattern that the highest efficiency is attained in areas of least flood risk. Both technical and allocative inefficiency effects are modelled as a function of farm-specific socioeconomic, resource, and institutional factors. The results from both the approaches indicate that efficiency is significantly influenced by the age, education, extension personnel visits, land fragmentation, and credit factors.
