AB  - Thirteen papers, most based on presentations made at the 2012 "Changements climatiques et agriculture" colloquium held in Montreal, investigate how human activities such as agriculture can adapt to climate change and variability (CCV). Papers discuss agricultural adaptation to changing environments--lessons learned from farmers in Eastern Ontario; an analysis of power relations among actors and institutions in the process of agricultural adaptation to climate change and variability from the diffusion of innovations perspective; climate change and corn productivity in West Monteregie, Quebec--the steps from impacts anticipation to some adaptation potentialities; the economic impact of climate change on cash crop farms in Quebec and Ontario; the organizational dimensions of agricultural adaptation--experiences in Quebec's market-garden sector; citizen involvement and volunteering along the Acadian coastline--challenges for integrated management and adaptation in the context of climate change; the contribution of agronomic research to innovation--the experience of the National Institute for Agricultural Research-Sciences for Action and Development (INRA-SAD) in France; low-frequency winter rainfall variability in the northwest of Morocco; projections of peanut yields from 2011 to 2040 in Senegal using classification and regression trees; facing climate change through sustainable agriculture--whether results from China can be transferred to Africa; adaptation strategies in the valley of the Senegal River--a social approach to dealing with climate change in Senegal; and adaptations of the agricultural calendar and agricultural techniques to climate change in the highlands of Cameroon. Bryant is at Universite de Montreal and with the School of Environmental Design and Rural Planning at the University of Guelph. Sarr is at Universite de Montreal and Centre de Suivi Ecologique. Delusca is at the Institut des Technologies et des Etudes Avancees d'Haiti. Index.
