TY  - GEN
AB  - This dissertation contains three pieces of empirical research in agricultural and experimental economics. The first piece examines the impacts of droughts and drought-induced water usage restrictions (curtailments) on the agriculture sector in Central Washington. My research explores how and to what extend limited irrigation water availability could affect the agriculture sector in the interested area. I consider two models and integrate them into a biophysical-agroeconomic system. The first model accounts for crops' biophysical responses to droughts and curtailments, and the second model studies farmers' agroeconomic response to droughts and curtailments. I assess the biophysical model, simulate farmers' expectations of yields, and pass them to the agroeconomic model. Then, I assess farmers' responses to drought with the agroeconomic model. I find that droughts and curtailments negatively impact crop yields, but their effects on crops planted acreages vastly vary. Some drought mitigation strategies are also discussed. The second research investigates China's aquaculture productivity after its the late 1970's economic reform. The aquaculture industry in China has been rapidly growing in the past four decades, but whether the growth should be attributed to productivity improvement or input expansion is mainly unknown. This research develops an empirical framework to examine the underlying factors that promote output growth, including aquaculture productivity, technological progress, and scale effects in China's aquaculture sector. I find that productivity in China's aquaculture sector has been steadily growing, and the leading cause of the productivity growth is technical progress rather than scale effects. The third study investigates interactions between consumers' quality expectations of animal products with animal welfare attributes and their consumption behaviors. Consumers' awareness of animal welfare influences their willingness to pay for animal products, and the awareness could also induce a higher expectation of quality that animal welfare products may convey. This research investigates one's quality expectation, leverages empirical data from experimental auctions, and analyzes one's purchase motivation on their consumption. I find that impacts of the quality expectation on one's willingness to pay are relatively minimal, and the moral concerns may be a decisive factor.
