AB  - Twenty-five papers, resulting from the 2014 Microenergy Systems-Berkeley Rural Energy Group Symposium at the University of California, Berkeley, present approaches to improving energy access in underprivileged communities using decentralized approaches and small-scale localized solutions. Papers discuss swarm electrification--investigating a paradigm shift through the building of microgrids bottom-up; identifying hidden resources in solar home systems as the basis for bottom-up grids; a concept of direct current nanogrid for low-cost energy access in rural Bangladesh; experience from the first solar minigrid service in Bangladesh; prospects for electricity access in rural India using solar photovoltaic based minigrid systems; the case for solar-diesel hybrid minigrids in Bangladesh--design considerations; a simulation gaming approach to microgrid design and planning--participatory design and capacity building; the energy center model--an approach to village scale energy supply; lessons from the edge--the US Army's experience meeting energy needs on the Afghan battlefields; value chain thinking and energy projects--a problem-centered value chain approach to energy-based upgrading of rice farmers in the Philippines; advanced solar-irrigation scheduling for sustainable rural development--a case of India; moving toward a waste management system for solar home systems in Bangladesh; how to scale up green microfinance--a comparative study of energy lending in Peru; microfinancing decentralized solar energy systems in India--innovative products through a group approach; innovative energy access for remote areas--the "Light up a Village" project; exploring the barriers to impact investing in the sustainable energy area in West Africa; the synergies between mobile phone access and off-grid energy solutions; optimizing device operation with a local electricity price; financing energy efficiency and climate adaptation measures on household levels in Kyrgyzstan--market-based approaches in a post-Soviet country; demand assessment of solar electrification in off-grid rural communities of Pakistan through microfinancing of solar home systems; scale versus substance--lessons from a context-responsive approach to market-based stove development in Western Kenya; health risks from indoor air pollution via inefficient domestic cooking and lighting fuel sources; an analysis of decision making for off-grid rural electrification in Colombia; barriers and solutions to the development of renewable energy technologies in the Caribbean; and the role of gender concerns in the planning of small-scale energy projects in developing countries. Groh is Director of ME SOLshare Ltd. and ME Fosera Ltd. Van der Straeten is a PhD candidate with Microenergy Systems at the Technische Universitat Berlin. Edlefsen Lasch is a solar engineer at EPC company ib vogt GmbH. Gershenson is a PhD candidate in the Energy and Resources group at the University of California, Berkeley. Leal Filho is Senior Professor at Hamburg University of Applied Sciences and Chair of Environment and Technology at Manchester Metropolitan University. Kammen is Class of 1935 Distinguished Professor of Energy at the University of California, Berkeley. No index.
