AB  - Twenty papers, many presented at the October 2013 conference "Transforming Rural Livelihoods in Africa" held in Nakuru, Kenya, examine the contribution of land and water management to enhanced food security and climate change adaptation and mitigation in the African continent. Papers discuss adapting agriculture to climate change by developing promising strategies using analogue locations in Eastern and Southern Africa--a systematic approach to develop practical solutions; improving livelihoods in semiarid regions of Africa through reduced vulnerability to climate variability and promotion of climate resilience; climate change adaptation planning in Kenya--whether scientific evidence really counts; a situation analysis of climate change aspects in Kenya; seasonal rainfall variability and drought characterization--the case of the eastern arid region of Kenya; addressing the potential impacts of climate change and variability on agricultural crops and water resources in the Pennar River Basin of Andhra Pradesh; grain yield responses of selected crop varieties at two pairs of temperature analogue sites in subhumid and semiarid areas of Zimbabwe; adapting agriculture to climate change--an evaluation of yield potential of maize, sorghum, common bean, and pigeon pea varieties in a very cool-wet region of Nyandarua County, Central Kenya; an assessment of gender sensitive adaptation options to climate change in smallholder areas of Zimbabwe, using climate analogue analysis; the impact of climate change and adaptation measures initiated by farmers; in situ soil moisture conservation--utilization and management of rainwater for crop production; enhancing food production in semiarid coastal lowlands Kenya through water harvesting technologies; opportunities for coping with climate change and variability through adoption of soil and water conservation technologies in semiarid Eastern Kenya; adoption of water resource conservation under fluctuating rainfall regimes in the Ngaciuma/Kinyaritha watershed, Meru County, Kenya; the effects of integration of irrigation water and mineral nutrient management in seed potato (Solanum Tuberosum L.) production on water, nitrogen, and phosphorus use efficiencies; integrating farmer perceptions and scientific methods for evaluating climate change adaptation options in Embu County; on-station evaluation of maize genotypes for nutrient and water use efficiency in the semiarid lands of coastal Kenya; tomato (Lycopersicon Esculentum Mill.) yield performance under elevated dry season temperatures as an adaptation to climate change in Tabora, Tanzania; drought mitigating technologies--an overview of cassava and sweet potato production in the Mukuyuni division of the Makueni district in semiarid Eastern Kenya; and how cassava farming transforms livelihoods among smallholder farmers in Mutomo, a semia-arid district in Kenya. Leal Filho is in the Faculty of Life Sciences at Hamburg University of Applied Sciences. Esilaba is at the Kenya Agricultural Research Institute. Rao and Sridhar are at the International Crops Research Institute for Semi-Arid Tropics. No index.
