AB  - Twenty-one papers investigate the socioeconomic impacts of climate change in the Asia-Pacific region and what countries there need to do to prepare for future impacts. Papers discuss livelihood vulnerability and displacement in coastal Bangladesh--understanding the nexus; the application of the macroeconomics analysis of climate changes model (MACC-Model) in China--floods; Kastom, climate change, and intergenerational democracy--experiences from Vanuatu; urban poor women and climate change in India--enhancing adaptive capacity through communication for development; local community perception of climate change and scientific validation--a review of initiatives and perspectives in the Indian region; managing environmental migration to improve economic and social outcomes in developing Asia and the Pacific; urban environmental governance--Bangladesh as a case in point; the economic value of cyclonic storm-surge risks--a hedonic case study of residential property in Exmouth, Western Australia; understanding the role of trust in network-based responses to disaster management and climate-change adaptation in the Asia-Pacific region; local adaptation to climate change--a case study among the indigenous Palaw'ans in the Philippines; managing "climate migration" in Mongolia--the importance of development policies; climate change and adaptation challenges in the Pacific; the strategic partnerships on climate change in the Asia-Pacific context--dynamics of Sino-US cooperation; strengthening climate-change adaptation in Nepal--needs and perspectives; climate change policy and sustainable-energy development in Fiji--implications for Pacific Island states; building resilience to climate-change impacts and socioeconomic attributes of rural households in the Solomon Islands; the significance of contextual vulnerability in effective adaptation to climate change on Tuvalu; pathways for climate-resilient livelihoods--the case of large cardamom farming in the Dzongu Valley of the Tista River Basin, Sikkim Himalaya; progress toward low-carbon fuels in the Pacific--prospects and challenges; moving toward low-carbon hotels in the Pacific Region--a study of energy consumption and efficiency in hotels using models based on energy performance indicators; and integrating technologies, measures, and policies for a climate-resilient economy--a case analysis from emerging countries in the Asia-Pacific Region. Leal Filho is in the Faculty of Life Sciences at the Hamburg University of Applied Sciences. No index.
