AB  - Sixteen papers by researchers supported by the Economy and Environment Program for Southeast Asia (EEPSEA) apply cost-benefit analysis techniques in the management of the environment and natural resources in developing countries of the Southeast Asian region. Papers discuss the principles and practice of cost-benefit analysis; a cost-benefit analysis of Jatropha biodiesel; comparing the social costs of biofuels and fossil fuels--a case study of Vietnam; an economic analysis of rice straw management alternatives and understanding farmers' choices; optimal forest management for carbon sequestration--a case study of Eucalyptus urophylla and Acacia magnium in Yen Bai Provence, Vietnam; rubber plantation development in Cambodia--a cost-benefit analysis; environmental consequences of, and pollution control options for, pond "tra" fish production in Thotnot District, Can Tho City, Vietnam; the application of an educated trade-off analysis framework for the Ma Oya River Basin Development Project, Sri Lanka; policy options for sustainable river sand mining in Sri Lanka; a cost-benefit analysis of ecotourism--a case study of the Xe Pian National Protected Area, Champasak Province, Lao People's Democratic Republic; a cost and benefit analysis of the community forestry project in Chumkiri District, Kampot Province, Cambodia; the economic benefit of management options for a suburban forest (Kho Hong Hill) in South Thailand; the cost-effectiveness of policy options for sustainable wetland conservation--a case study of Qixinghe Wetland, China; economic vulnerability and possible adaptation to coastal erosion in San Fernando City, Philippines; the adaptation to sea level rise in the Vietnamese Mekong River Delta--whether a sea dike should be built; and exploring the potentials of a technology-based flood early warning system in Laguna, Philippines--a cost-benefit analysis. James is a resource person with the Economy and Environment Program for Southeast Asia (EEPSEA) and a consultant. Francisco is with the EEPSEA at WorldFish. Index.
