AB  - Eleven papers examine which people around the world have adapted (struggled, or failed to adapt) culturally to changing economic conditions caused by climate change and/or shifts in environmental quality, using the technique of intensive ethnographic investigation. Papers discuss institutional climate change adaptation efforts among the Sherpas of the Mount Everest region, Nepal (Pasang Yangjee Sherpa); installing rooftop solar panels in private homes--the case of small electricity producers on Reunion Island in the Indian Ocean (Sophie Bouly de Lesdain); "bug wood"--climate change, mountain pine beetles, and risk in the southeastern British Columbia logging industry (Patrick B. Patterson); conservation units, environmental services, and frontier peasants in the Central Amazon--the questions of multifunctionality, juxtaposition, or conflict (Ana Maria de Souza Mello Bicalho and Scott William Hoefle); the question of global warming or cash economy--discourses of climate change and food in Eastern Highlands Province, Papua New Guinea (Olivia Barnett-Naghshineh); farmers' rainfall anticipation--incidence and patterns in Western Nigeria--advantages of focus and problems of extrapolation in case studies (Jane I. Guyer); climate change policies and the adaptive behavior of farmers in southern China (Meine Pieter van Dijk and Hao Li); whether environmental uncertainty is redefining fishing strategies--the use of the traditional lunar calendar to allocate fishing effort in Ende, Eastern Indonesia (Victoria C. Ramenzoni); the origins of the sustainability concept--risk perception and resource management in early urban centers (Monica L. Smith); merchant resiliency and climate hazard vulnerability in the urban Philippines--anthropological perspectives on the 2011 Typhoons Nesat and Nalgae (Ty Matejowsky); and environmental destruction, Guarani refugees, and indigenous identity in urban Paraguay (Richard K. Reed). Wood is Associate Professor in the Graduate School of Medicine at Akita University. No index.
