AB  - Twenty-one papers address emerging issues related to climate variation, climate changes, and adaptation technology, focusing on Latin American countries. Papers discuss the regional vulnerability of agro-environmental processes facing climate change--Latin American adaptation agendas; risk analysis in transboundary water of the Pilcomayo and Paraguay rivers ; an analysis of temporal variability of droughts in Southern Paraguay and Northern Argentina (1961-2011); the sedimentation and life expectancy of Lake Amatitlan, Guatemala--increased vulnerability under future climate change; a move toward valuing climate change impacts on the ecosystem services of a Uruguayan coastal lagoon; integrating climate science, monitoring, and management in the Rio de la Plata Estuarine Front (Uruguay); managing the impacts of climate change in Latin America--the need for technology transfer; strategic contributions to extreme climate change--the innovation helixes as a link among the short, medium, and long terms; what contributes to climate change adaptive capacity--a retrospective case study in a Caribbean small island community; taking a microperspective on the global challenge of climate change--the "microenergy systems" research focus at the Technische Universitat Berlin; the impacts of climate change on the livelihoods of coastal people in Bangladesh--a sociological study; from rainforests to drylands--comparing family farmers' perceptions of climate change in three Brazilian biomes; precipitation variability and adaptation strategies in the Southern Yucatan Peninsula, Mexico--integrating local knowledge with quantitative analysis; making science count--climate change and the science/practice interface; island erosion and afflicted population--crisis and policies to handle climate change; whether awareness through learning about climate change enhances farmers' perception of, and adaptation to, climate uncertainty; local knowledge and participatory climate change planning in the Northeastern United States; evaluating post-2012 carbon policies; perceptions about climate change in Sidama, Ethiopia; perceptions of, and attitudes toward, climate change in the Southeastern United States; and the role of higher education in institutionalizing climate change in Bangladesh. Leal Filho is with the International Climate Change Information Programme at Hamburg University of Applied Sciences. Alves and Azeiteiro are at Universidade Alberta. Caeiro is at Universidade Alberta Campus do Taguspark. No index.
