AB  - Eighteen papers, previously presented at a conference entitled "Environments of the Poor" and held in New Delhi in November 2010, and revised, provide examples of possible triple-win solutions for reducing poverty, protecting the environment, and responding to climate change in Southeast Asia, East Asia, and the Pacific. Papers discuss poverty, environment, and climate change in the grasslands of China; climate change, food security, and poverty in the People's Republic of China; the physical and social environment of the Chinese urban poor; benefiting the poor, the environment, and the private sector with small enterprises and green jobs in the People's Republic of China; the environment, economic growth, and poverty in the Republic of Korea; climate change adaptation and poverty reduction in small islands of the Pacific; the role of development organizations in pro-poor adaptation to global warming in the Pacific islands; poverty and the environment in rural Cambodia; conservation agriculture in Cambodia--a triple-win option; voices of the poor on climate change in Thailand and Vietnam; poor Thai farmers' adaptation to climate change; the political economy of environmental policy in Indonesia; prospering in environmental degradation--an illustration from an upland area, South Kalimantan, Indonesia; making a living in the face of environmental change--a case in an indigenous community in Sarawak, Malaysia; the response of rural coastal households to Typhoon Milenyo in the Philippines; life along Manila's flooding rivers; quantifying the health risks from pathogens in the flood water in metro Manila; and slum poverty in the Philippines--whether the environment agenda can drive public action. Ananta is Senior Research Fellow at the Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS), Singapore. Bauer is Principal Economist in the Asian Development Bank's Regional and Sustainable Development Department. Thant is with the Asian Development Bank. No index.
