AB  - Twenty papers demonstrate that new threats to food security which arise from environmental change can be addressed with an integrated food system approach. Papers discuss a mitigation-adaptation nexus for sustainability--some important crosscutting and emerging considerations; climate change impacts in the Arab region--a review of adaptation and mitigation potential and practices; mainstreaming agriculture for climate change mitigation--a public administration perspective; learning about climate change--a case study of grain growers in Eastern Australia; the economic impact of climate change on agriculture in the semiarid tropics (SAT) of India--an empirical analysis of impacts in Andhra Pradesh using a Ricardian approach; vulnerability to climate change in SAT India--scouting for a holistic approach; sustainable agriculture and rural development in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia--implications for agricultural extension and education; the economic impact of climate change on Tunisian agriculture--the case of wheat; greenhouse gas mitigation options in Greek dairy sheep farming--a multiobjective programming approach; adaptation strategies of citrus and tomato farmers toward the effect of climate change in Nigeria; an ex ante impact assessment of "stay-green" drought tolerant sorghum cultivar under future climate scenarios--an integrated modeling approach; the impact of climate changes on water resources in Algeria; drought tolerance of different wheat species (Triticum L.); coping with climate change through water harvesting techniques for sustainable agriculture in Rwanda; climate change and biotechnology--a toolkit for food fish security; climate change and fisheries in Chile; livelihoods of coastal communities in Mnazi Bay-Ruvuma Estuary Marine Park, Tanzania; livelihood strategy in Indonesian coastal villages--a case study on seaweed farming in Laikang Bay, South Sulawesi Province; monosex fish production in fisheries management and its potentials for catfish aquaculture in Nigeria; and a stock assessment of bogue, Boops boops (Linnaeus, 1758) from the Egyptian Mediterranean waters. Behnassi is Associate Professor and Head of the Public Law Department at Ibn Zohr University of Agadir. Gopichandran is Director of Vigyan Prasar of the Department of Science and Technology for the Government of India. Shelat is with the National Council for Climate Change, Sustainable Development, and Public Leadership in Ahmedabad. No index.
