AB  - My dissertation is comprised of three chapters that explore development, migration, and poverty in rural Mexico and Nigeria. The first two chapters broadly investigate the determinants of and impacts of migration with data from Mexico while the third chapter tests the presence of poverty traps in northern Nigeria. The unifying concept threaded throughout the chapters is the study of decision making by poor, rural households and individuals, experiencing shocks at times in equilibrium at others, in the context of risk and incomplete markets. Another feature of this work is the careful accounting of motives and mechanisms, to the extent possible, associated with labor decisions and endowment allocations. These may relate to risk diversification, non-pecuniary motives such as family reunification and forced returns, or land use in response to population growth. I also pay special attention to the role that gender plays in shaping migration and labor outcomes in the two chapters where I study individual level behavior, appreciating gender as a form of fundamental heterogeneity that must be accounted for to fully understand economic development, migration and poverty. Although my research is centered within economics, many of the questions I consider transcend traditional boundaries. As such, my scholarship also incorporates an integrative lens that is informed by demography, sociology and environmental sciences, among other areas of study. The first chapter assesses whether individuals in Mexico engage in anticipatory (ex ante) migration or local labor reallocation in response to observing heat induced catastrophic crop losses of other households within their communities. The main contribution of this study is in demonstrating that individuals mitigate against the increased probability of destabilizing climate events in an anticipatory manner, particularly through domestic migration, substantiating rarely studied ex ante concepts. This work additionally shows that agriculture is a major, if not the dominant, mechanism through which the environment influences migration in rural areas while drawing attention to the salience of learning about environmental risk and the crop losses of others. In so doing, this study highlights that the observation of low levels of adaptation to climate change (aka adaptation gaps) may be partially explained by the nearly exclusive focus on reactive (ex post) responses to environmental phenomena. These findings and the heterogeneous capacity of households to mitigate the risks associated with climate shocks have important implications for and the design, targeting and implementation of climate change mitigation programs. I integrate panel socioeconomic data from the Mexican Family Life Survey with georeferenced, high temporal resolution weather data from the Agricultural Modern-Era Retrospective Analysis for Research and Applications Climate Forcing Dataset for Agricultural Modeling to evaluate the anticipatory migration hypothesis. I develop an approach that credibly disentangles ex ante from ex post responses to temperature-induced catastrophic crop losses. This requires focusing on the behavior of households who have not recently experienced catastrophic crop losses in response to the observable heat induced shocks faced by other households in their communities. Identification also requires instrumenting for the extent of community-level crop losses with variation in plausibly exogenous temperature extremes to address endogeneity associated with vulnerability to crop losses, as well as to pin down the climate-agriculture-labor mechanism. I find evidence of domestic migration in anticipation of future crop shocks, particularly among women and households with more labor and previous migration experience. I find an increase in domestic migration of 2.6-3 percentage points from 2002 to 2003 and 2003 to 2005, respectively, which represent proportionally large responses of 52 to 120 percent. Notably, the majority of migrants temporarily relocate to a city, other state or country, which is consistent with spatial diversification to climate risk. I also show evidence of local labor reallocation onto household land (agricultural self-employment), especially among men and households with less labor and more land, which is most likely attributable to changes in the local demand for and value of agricultural labor as opposed to anticipation. I find an increase in agricultural self-employment of 8.5 percentage points increase in 2002, much of which is offset by a decrease in non-agricultural wage work. This response also constitutes a proportionally large responses (approximately 50 percent). I find that ex ante migration and local labor reallocations are substantial, ranging from 25 to 60 percent of the total migration and local labor response, which is a larger share than expected. The second chapter is a collaboration with Bradford L. Barham exploring the direct influence of migration and return migration on occupation outcomes for individuals from rural, coffee producing households in southern Mexico. This study focuses on the impact of labor mobility on occupation trajectories in conjunction with the motives and selection dynamics shaping migration. The principal contribution of this study is in demonstrating that occupation outcomes are directly and positively influenced by both migration and return migration, especially for females, net of the positive selection associated with migration and the negative selection associated with non-pecuniary factors. We provide a fuller description of the migration-labor relationship than previous studies in considering the influence of migration and return migration, only one of which is typically feasible due to data limitations, while also carefully accounting for positive and negative selection processes. These results highlight the positive welfare effects of labor mobility for the rural poor and the losses associated with non-pecuniary motives, such as family reunification or forced returns. We extend the Roy Model to account for unobservable characteristics related to non-pecuniary migration motives and link the data generating process to an econometric strategy that explicitly accounts for the complex selection based dimensions of how migration and return migration influence occupational outcomes for women and men (separately). This is accomplished by specifying a Mixed Nonlinear Endogenous Switching Regression, an extension of conventional Heckman and Endogenous Switching Regression procedures, which exploits non-linear outcomes to generate estimates of the direct impacts of migration and return migration on occupation outcomes while controlling for selection associated with unobserved heterogeneity. Identification is achieved through a combination of non-linearities inherent to the structure of the model and via variation in the size or duration of community migration networks. We find that migration and return migration choices have a positive effect on occupational outcomes for women and men. The average positive marginal effect of migration on occupation outcomes ranges from 72% for females and 70% for males, while the average positive marginal effect on occupation outcomes of return migration ranges from 44% for females to 21% for males. We additionally find that occupation outcomes associated with migration and return migration are clearly and distinctly selected for both women and men. The negative selection associated with non-pecuniary motives for the occupation outcomes of migrants ranges from -0.64 for females to -0.68 for males, while the negative selection for the occupation outcomes of return migrants ranges from -0.41 for women and close to zero for males. The third chapter explores asset dynamics and the presence of poverty traps in northern Nigeria over a 20-year period and is coauthored with Andrew Dillon (Northwestern University). The primary contribution of this paper is in consistently presenting evidence that does not support the poverty traps hypothesis among rural, agricultural households in a remote part of Nigeria despite testing for them (i) over a relatively long time horizon; (ii) in a setting where livestock is "##! the primary, but not exclusive, asset accumulated by households; (iii) for a diverse set of assets including land, livestock, capital, and durables; as well as (iv) using parametric and semiparametric estimation techniques. We also account for the distinct trajectories over time of original vs. split households, and dynastic (aggregate) household units that may better reflect intergenerational asset dynamics. Finally, we show that agricultural land extensification (bringing new land into cultivation beyond intensification) in response to population pressure may explain why households are able to achieve slow growth and asset wealth mobility, thereby avoiding poverty traps. Our results underscore the important role that access to productive land can play in promoting welfare. We find evidence of non-linearities in asset dynamics, but do not find evidence of nonconvexities and thresholds that are indicative of poverty traps. Our results reject several different types of poverty traps including single, multiple equilibrium and geographical poverty traps. This remains true for split, original and dynastic households units, but these distinct household definitions do lead to different asset accumulation trajectories. We also provide evidence of a more than 10-fold increase in the cultivation of irrigable land. This largescale extensification of agricultural land (beyond intensification) is accompanied by a substantial increase in livestock prices, particularly among cows and bullocks for ploughing whose price increased nearly 16-fold.
