AB  - Twenty papers explore the impact of climate change in agriculture and consider how agriculture is able to adapt to such change. Papers discuss climate change, carbon dioxide, and global crop production--food security and uncertainty; the effects of climate variability on domestic livestock; the move from the farmer to global food production--the use of crop models for climate change impact assessment; investigating the connections between climate change, drought, and agricultural production; farm-level impacts of climate change--alternative approaches for modeling uncertainty; using panel data models to estimate the economic impacts of climate change on agriculture; the impact of climate change on U.S. agriculture--a repeated cross-sectional Ricardian analysis; economywide impacts of climate change on agriculture--a case study for adaptation strategies in sub-Saharan Africa; integrated assessment models--the interplay of climate change, agriculture, and land use in a policy tool; the role of growth and trade in agricultural adaptation to environmental change; biofuels and climate change; the present and future role for agricultural projects under the Clean Development Mechanism; agricultural adaptation--needs, findings, and effects; hydro-economic modeling to assess climate impact and adaptation for agriculture in California; reducing the impact of global climate change on agriculture--the use of endogenous irrigation and protected agriculture technology; climate change and technological innovation in agriculture--adaptation through science; adaptation to climate change in mixed crop-livestock farming systems in developing countries; insurance as an adaptation to climate variability in agriculture; an analysis of the choice of livestock species under global warming in African and Latin American farms; and climate change, drought, and agriculture--the role of effective institutions and infrastructure. Dinar is Professor of Environmental Economics and Policy in the Department of Environmental Sciences and Director of the Water Science and Policy Center at the University of California, Riverside. Mendelsohn is Edwin Weyerhaeuser Davis Professor at Yale University. Index.
