AB  - The Barak Valley, located on the southernmost fringe of Assam, bordering Bangladesh, is one of those regions in the country which has for long remained on the sidelines of development. Agricultural practices in the region are characterised by single cropping, low productivity and frequent flooding while large-scale industries are almost non-existent. In this backdrop, this paper uses micro level data from 16 villages to assess the role of non-farm incomes among rural households in the region. The paper finds that owing to the seasonal character of agricultural practices, rural households are highly diversified and in fact, the largest share of household incomes is derived from non-farm sources. However, considerable variations are observed across the income groups in terms of the composition of income with poorer households found to be more dependent on agricultural income. The study also reveals that specific types of non-farm income have a large inequality-producing effect, which underscores the need for removing the entry barriers associated with such non-farm occupations.
