AB  - The contribution of agriculture to overall gross domestic product (GDP) of the country declined from 44.5 per cent in 1970-71 to around 20.0 per cent in 2005-06 to 17 per cent in the current (as per Economic Survey). The farmer is heavily dependent on market for input and faces ever increasing input costs despite massive subsidy for fertilizers. The input, output, and credit related issues that make the farmer vulnerable. Credit plays an important role in enabling the farmers to carry on the agricultural activities. The list of measures introduced by Governments both Central and State, and regulators and supervisors, Reserve Bank of India, and NABARD, to mitigate the various risks that a farmer or a rural non-farm worker/unit faces include minimum support price (SAP for sugarcane farmers), farm income insurance, credit guarantee, general insurance, crop insurance, subsidies, waivers, interest concessions, one time settlements (OTS), and rescheduling/conversion of loan instalments/payments, etc. Bank loans are limited in quantum, issued for a particular purpose only, often the disbursement is made to a third party like an unknown pumpset dealer etc., interest is payable half yearly. In the case of crop loan, the loan is normally repayable in about nine months time and term loans are repayable in annual instalments. The average loan period is 5 years. Currently a borrower/farmer is declared a defaulter on account of reasons such as drought, flood, market failure, etc. often leading to helplessness and suicidal tendencies among the farming community. The study has suggested two measures, viz. a compound loan for the farmer and risk management measures to minimize the burden faced by the farmers and also the banks in loan recovery. This will contribute to reducing the incidence of suicidal tendencies among the farmers. More importantly these measures will ensure that in future no massive waivers would be necessary.
