AB  - One of the main barriers limiting farmers' integration into markets in developing countries is the inadequate coverage and quality of the rural road networks, which result in high transaction costs and exclusion from social and economic facilities. These high transaction costs constrain poor smallholder farmers in remote rural areas into a restricted set of opportunities and a narrow range of access to facilities and markets limiting their ability to sell their fresh produce directly to the public and generate additional income. The isolation of farmers from markets provides a significant explanation for the regional dimension of poverty and economic development. Just like long distances to schools lead to low school enrollment and long distances to health care facilities lead to higher mortality during child birth, farmers' isolation from markets drive up the fraction of the agricultural workforce that experiences difficulty in generating income and meeting basic needs. Improving the quality of rural roads reduces the cost of arranging transactions between spatially separate locations and can significantly affect agricultural market prices, consumption expenditures, and poverty levels. This dissertation takes advantage of the partial implementation of a rural road rehabilitation project in western Nicaragua to identify changes in market prices attributed to improving rural road quality and calculates the magnitude these price changes would represent of a typical rural household's basket of consumer goods. In 2005, the Millennium Challenge Corporation (MCC), a United States foreign aid agency, signed a $175 million compact with the Government of Nicaragua to help reduce transportation costs, improve access to markets, and raise incomes for farmers and rural businesses in western Nicaragua. After widespread irregularities during the November 2008 municipal elections, the MCC terminated a portion of the compact, reducing funding from $175 million to $113.5 million and cancelling the rehabilitation of rural roads that were not already under contract. A substantial improvement in road quality resulted from the MCC's rehabilitation of a secondary rural route connecting the communities of Poneloya and Las Penitas in the Pacific coast to the city of Leon. Meanwhile, the rehabilitation of the 8.3-mile road Santa ix Teresa-Las Brisas was cancelled and it remained in poor condition. Price and availability surveys regarding 53 goods were collected at grocery stores before and after the intervention both along the treated road, Leon-Poneloya-Las Penitas, and the untreated road, Santa Teresa-Las Brisas. The Millennium Challenge Corporation (MCC) rehabilitated the road from Leon to Poneloya and Las Penitas in Western Nicaragua, which provides a simple scenario for this study. Leon is the second largest city in Nicaragua. The fishing port of Poneloya and the coastal village of Las Penitas are both beach communities that are becoming popular tourist destinations. The road that connects these communities to Leon was substantially rehabilitated at a cost of $21 million. Before the project the road's 12.2-mile surface was paved but in a very poor condition, as indicated by a baseline International Roughness Index (IRI) of 12.0, which fell to 1.84 after the rehabilitation. The average running speed of vehicles was about 35 miles/hour resulting in increased operating costs and travel times. The rehabilitation of the road was performed on the existing route with no noticeable changes on its alignment and it helped strengthen pavement structures, minor and major drainage structures, sidewalks and shoulders, significantly improving the road's quality and reliability, including during severe weather. The rehabilitation of this rural road connecting an isolated coastal area to the city of Leon in western Nicaragua substantially improved the quality of the road's surface. As a result, a significant reduction in transportation costs and travel times was expected to improve rural households' access to modern urban markets. The degree to which the resulting impacts on market prices for locally-produced goods could effectively ameliorate poverty and income inequality in the coast as a consequence of the project will depend on the heterogeneous distribution of the road's benefits. In the area of influence of the rehabilitated road, where fishing is the main source of income and poverty is either high or severe, it was found that improving the road could have benefited the poorest households by lowering the average cost of a basic basket of goods and by allowing fresh fish caught in the coast to be sold in urban x markets. This dissertation is broadly motivated by how challenging it has been to prove empirically whether road improvements raise the incomes of poor households in developing countries. Taken together, these three essays address the issue of how a significant rural road rehabilitation might allow isolated rural households to be better connected to markets for their inputs and outputs, which should be reflected significantly on their income. In the first essay, a difference in difference in differences (DDD) estimation strategy measures the resulting changes in markups between Leon and the stores located along the treated road, which can be attributed more certainly to the road improvement if this same effect cannot also be found along the untreated road. The treatment effect is aggregated across goods according to the Nicaraguan government's definition of a six-member household's typical consumption basket. The results provide evidence that the rural road improvement narrowed the gap between urban and rural prices by lowering the prices of some manufactured goods (e.g. toothpaste) and raising the prices of locally produced goods (e.g. fresh fish caught in the coast). In particular, price changes that result from a better connection to markets benefited poor households by lowering the average cost of a basic basket of consumer goods by -1.69%. Fishers, who are likely to be among the extremely poor households, benefited from the price of fresh fish caught in the coast rising by 31.9%. Consumers in small and remote communities face higher prices and fewer varieties of consumer goods, which contribute to worse living standards. Intermediaries incur higher transportation costs when selling to remote cities, making prices higher in these markets. Due to limited transportation infrastructure, consumption opportunities in small and remote cities in developing countries are especially limited. The second essay provides a theoretical model where a reduction in transportation costs after a road improvement makes it easier and cheaper for products to be delivered to stores, but also makes stores compete for customers more strenuously. A road rehabilitation would have two different effects. On the one hand, the direct transportation cost effect, which makes it less expensive to deliver goods to stores. xi On the other hand, the competition effect, which unlocks consumers' access to new markets reducing stores' market power defined as their ability to price above marginal cost. These two effects would allow to explain, for example, why stores in the middle of the road, being in a less competitive environment, could be the ones with the highest ability to charge above their marginal cost when the road is rough. After the road was fixed, these stores in the middle of the road lose their market power as consumers located in small villages can now travel more easily to either Leon or Poneloya-Las Penitas and are no longer willing to purchase goods at high prices. Finally, the third essay explores how farmers would benefit, not only from a reduction in the transaction costs of purchasing inputs and selling outputs, but from a reduction in the uncertainty of these costs. The main challenge for the road sector in Nicaragua, as in many other developing countries, is to improve the quality of the existing roads rather than to increase the extension of its road network. The low quality of rural roads in Nicaragua is aggravated by heavy traffic, geographic conditions and the high frequency of floods. Heavy vehicles, such as trucks and other equipment used in agriculture, are harder on roads than cars. For example, a fully loaded tractor-trailer is 20 times heavier than a passenger car and its impact on the roadway is disproportionately larger. Roads in rural areas with wet and mountainous terrain face substantially higher costs of maintenance than those in flat and arid terrain and must be fixed frequently in order to be in fair condition. High rainfall accelerates the process of road deterioration, requiring frequent and more intensive maintenance interventions. If water is allowed to stand on the road surface after it rains, vehicles create potholes that eventually discourage rural households' participation in markets by affecting the cost of traveling and the safety of all road users.
