AB  - This dissertation explores the current conditions and operations of the markets for seven key food security crops (maize, millet, sorghum, rice, cassava, yams, and cowpeas) in Nigeria. The findings of the three studies in this dissertation will be useful for policymakers and stakeholders who are actively pursuing initiatives to reduce short and long-run risk of food insecurity there. These results show that much progress needs to be made in terms of advancement in governance and institutional capacity at the local, state, and national levels in Nigeria, especially with regard to the gathering and dissemination of accurate and timely agricultural market data and removal of distortions that limit rural farmer access to markets. Chapter 2 is an empirical analysis of the current agricultural statistics system in Nigeria. Many international and national sources gather and report agricultural statistics for the country. Since there has not been an agricultural census implemented there for multiple decades, however, there is no viable source for verification and no plausible mechanism for obtaining a representative sample from which to accurately aggregate estimates. Thus, this study uses two additional types of "on the ground information" to assess whether existing agricultural production estimates reflect local conditions: prices and remote sensing data in the form of the normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), a commonly employed proxy for expected agricultural production. The results show that the existing production estimates are poorly correlated with both prices and NDVI data. Prices and NDVI data were, however, highly correlated with each other. These findings imply that the existing production estimates do not reflect local conditions and are, thus, of poor quality. Chapter 3 is a comprehensive analysis of crop price transmission from global and neighbor country prices to Nigerian urban markets, and from urban to other urban and rural markets within the country. These results show that tradability matters for price transmission, but that tradability varies across crops and scopes of markets. Urban rice prices are highly correlated with prices on global markets and those in neighboring countries. Coarse grain prices appear disconnected from global markets but move closely with those in neighboring countries. Large margins were estimated for prices of rice and coarse grains imported from global markets, but with some regional differences observed for coarse grains. The large margins are observed for coarse grains in Southern Nigerian markets, but in all regions for rice. The existence of large margins imply that there are either transactions costs and/or quality premiums that vary systematically with the world price and/or mark-ups by traders with market power. Lastly, long lags were found for price transmission across all scopes of markets, but especially between urban and rural prices in some regions. These results imply that local conditions (e.g., weather) are relatively more important than prices in other markets for explaining price variation in rural markets, especially in the short-run. Chapter 4 encompasses remote sensing NDVI data into price models to estimate the degree to which weather and production changes help explain price variation. The results show that the weather information is most informative for rural, isolated markets relative to urban markets. Even for those local prices, however, other non-weather and non-external market price factors are important for explanation of price variation. The results also support the conjecture that expectations on future harvest in the lean season period can intermittently change the degree to which prices in linked markets co-move. The food security implications of this dissertation are that Nigeria cannot plausibly rely solely on direct imports from global markets to meet short-run demand during periods exhibiting weather shocks in the future. Due to both long lags in trade from the ports and potentially imperfectly competitive traders that facilitate such imports, it is unlikely that cereals imported from global markets could be imported in a timely or xviii cost-effective manner to meet demand that arises from an unanticipated supply shortage. Thus, some storage facilities are required, either for storage of imports acquired during non-crisis periods or domestically produced surpluses, for use in occasional disaster responses. Since it was observed that rural areas are relatively less connected to urban markets than urban markets among themselves, strategic allocation of stored supplies such that they can be made available in the rural areas that are most at risk of weather anomalies as they arise is needed. This type of managed food security storage system will be required at least until other key market distortions that now raise the cost of trade between urban and rural markets are addressed, which will take considerable resources and time.
